Html:
I just encountered an Interesting behavior creating a brand new application.   &quot;The name 'InitializeComponent' does not exist in the current context&quot; happened after I added the following to see if it would resolve my issue of not being able to access App.xaml styles from my modules:<br />
<pre><code>        public App()
        {
            InitializeComponent();
        }</code></pre>

I found this odd as I had not encountered this problem until now - when I discovered the problem it made sense as I generally have merged dictionaries.   In your App.Xaml file you have to have the following:  &lt;ResourceDictionary.MergedDictionaries/&gt; <br />
<br />
With this statement you no longer require the constructor or InitializeComponent (and it works).<br />
<br />
Example follows:<br />
<pre><code>    &lt;Application.Resources&gt;
        &lt;ResourceDictionary&gt;
            &lt;ResourceDictionary.MergedDictionaries/&gt;
            &lt;Style TargetType=&quot;Button&quot;&gt;
                &lt;Setter Property=&quot;Command&quot; Value=&quot;{Binding GenericCommand}&quot;/&gt;
                &lt;Setter Property=&quot;CommandParameter&quot; Value=&quot;{Binding RelativeSource={RelativeSource Self}}&quot;/&gt;
            &lt;/Style&gt;            
        &lt;/ResourceDictionary&gt;
    &lt;/Application.Resources&gt;
</code></pre>
